# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: opc-classic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM is the basis for other Microsoft domain-specific component technologies including OLE, OLE Automation, ActiveX, COM+, and DCOM as well as implementations such as DirectX, Windows shell, UMDF, Windows Runtime, and Browser Helper Object.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM enables object use when only the object's interface is known, not its internal implementation.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] The component implementer defines interfaces that are separate from the implementation.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Support for multiple programming contexts is handled by relying on the object for aspects that would be challenging to implement as a facility.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Supporting multiple uses of an object is handled by requiring each object to destroy itself via reference-counting.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Access to an object's interfaces (similar to Type conversion) is provided by each object as well.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM is available only in Microsoft Windows and Apple's Core Foundation 1.3 and later plug-in application programming interface (API).
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] The latter only implements a subset of the whole COM interface.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Over time, COM is being replaced with other technologies such as Microsoft .NET and web services (i.e. via WCF).
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] However, COM objects can be used in a .NET language via COM Interop.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM is similar to other component technologies such as SOM, CORBA and Enterprise JavaBeans, although each has its strengths and weaknesses.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Unlike C++, COM provides a stable application binary interface (ABI) that is unaffected by compiler differences.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This makes using COM advantageous for object-oriented C++ libraries that are to be used by clients compiled via different compilers.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Introduced in 1987, Dynamic Data Exchange (DDE) was one of the first interprocess communication technologies in Windows.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] It allowed sending and receiving messages in so-called *conversations* between applications.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] These provided the foundation of many of the ideas behind COM.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Object Linking and Embedding (OLE), Microsoft's first object-based framework, was built on DDE and designed specifically for compound documents.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] It was introduced with Word and Excel in 1991, and was later included with Windows, starting with version 3.1 in 1992.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] An example of a compound document is a spreadsheet embedded in a Word document.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] As changes are made to the spreadsheet in Excel, they appear automatically in the Word document.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] In 1991, Microsoft introduced the Visual Basic Extension (VBX) technology with Visual Basic 1.0.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A VBX is a packaged extension in the form of a dynamic-link library (DLL) that allows objects to be graphically placed in a form and manipulated by properties and methods.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] These were later adapted for use by other languages such as Visual C++.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] In 1992, Microsoft released OLE 2 with its new underlying object model, COM.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] The COM application binary interface (ABI) was the same as the MAPI ABI (released in 1992), and like it was based on MSRPC and ultimately on the Open Group's DCE/RPC.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM was created to replace DDE since its text-based conversation and Windows messaging design was not flexible enough to allow sharing application features in a robust and extensible way.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] In 1994, the OLE custom control (OCX) technology, based on COM, was introduced as the successor to VBX.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] At the same time, Microsoft stated that OLE 2 would be known simply as "OLE".
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Windows NT 3.5 and Windows 95 integrated OLE 2.0.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] In early 1996, Microsoft found a new use for OCX – extending their web browser's capability.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Microsoft renamed some parts of OLE relating to the Internet as ActiveX, and gradually renamed all OLE technologies to ActiveX, except the compound document technology that was used in Microsoft Office.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Later in 1996, Microsoft extended COM to work across the network with DCOM.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] In 1997, Windows CE integrated support for COM.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] The COM IDL is based on the feature-rich DCE/RPC IDL, with object-oriented extensions.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Microsoft's implementation of DCE/RPC, **MSRPC**, is used as the primary inter-process communication mechanism for Windows NT services and internal components, making it an obvious choice of foundation.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] DCOM extends COM from merely supporting a single user with separate applications communicating on the Windows desktop, to activating objects running under different security contexts, and on different machines across the network.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] With this were added necessary features for configuring which users have authority to create, activate and call objects, for identifying the calling user, as well as specifying required encryption for security of calls.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Renamed to **COM+** in Windows 2000, the feature set was incorporated into the operating system as opposed to the series of external tools provided by MTS.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] At the same time, Microsoft de-emphasized DCOM as a separate entity.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Components that used COM+ were handled more directly by the added layer of COM+, in particular by operating system support for interception.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] In the first release of MTS, interception was tacked on – installing an MTS component would modify the Windows Registry to call the MTS software, and not the component directly.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Windows 2000 included Component Services control panel updates for configuring COM+ components.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] An advantage of COM+ was that it could be run in "component farms".
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Instances of a component, if coded properly, could be pooled and reused by new calls to its initializing routine without unloading it from memory.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Components could also be distributed (called from another machine).
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM+ and Microsoft Visual Studio provided tools to make it easy to generate client-side proxies, so although DCOM was used to make the remote call, it was easy to do for developers.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM+ also introduced a subscriber/publisher event mechanism called **COM+ Events**, and provided a new way of leveraging MSMQ (a technology that provides inter-application asynchronous messaging) with components called **Queued Components**.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM+ events extend the COM+ programming model to support late-bound (see Late binding) events or method calls between the publisher or subscriber and the event system.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] .NET provides wrappers to commonly used COM controls.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] .NET can leverage COM+ via the `System.EnterpriseServices` namespace, and several of the services that COM+ provides have been duplicated in .NET.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] For example, the `System.Transactions` namespace provides the `TransactionScope` class, which provides transaction management without resorting to COM+.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Similarly, queued components can be replaced by Windows Communication Foundation (WCF) with an MSMQ transport.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] There is limited support for backward compatibility.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A COM object may be used in .NET by implementing a Runtime Callable Wrapper (RCW).
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] NET objects that conform to certain interface restrictions may be used in COM objects by calling a *COM callable wrapper* (CCW).
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] From both the COM and .NET sides, objects using the other technology appear as native objects.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] WCF eases a number of COM's remote execution challenges.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] For instance, it allows objects to be transparently marshalled by value across process or machine boundaries more easily.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Some implementations of Nano-COM such as Direct3D eschew the allocator functions and restrict themselves to only use caller-allocated buffers.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Nano-COM has no notion of classes, apartments, marshaling, registration, etc.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Rather, object references are simply passed across function boundaries and allocated via standard language constructs (e.g., C++ `new` operator).
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Nano-COM is currently in use as the base ABI technology for DirectX/Direct3D/DirectML.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Since an ActiveX control (any COM component) runs as native code, with no sandboxing protection, there are few restrictions on what it can do.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Using ActiveX components, as Internet Explorer supported, in a web page lead to problems with malware infections.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Microsoft recognized the problem as far back as 1996 when Charles Fitzgerald said, "We never made the claim up front that ActiveX is intrinsically secure".
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Later versions of Internet Explorer prompt the user before installing an ActiveX control, allowing them to block installation.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] As a level of protection, an ActiveX control is signed with a digital signature to guarantee authenticity.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] It is also possible to disable ActiveX controls altogether, or to allow only a selected few.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] The transparent support for out-of-process COM servers promotes software safety in terms of process isolation.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This can be useful for decoupling subsystems of large application into separate processes.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Process isolation limits state corruption in one process from negatively affecting the integrity of the other processes, since they only communicate through strictly defined interfaces.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Thus, only the affected subsystem needs to be restarted in order to regain valid state.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This is not the case for subsystems within the same process, where a *rogue pointer* in one subsystem can randomly corrupt other subsystems.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM is supported via bindings in several languages, such as C, C++, Visual Basic, Delphi, Python and several of the Windows scripting contexts.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Component access is via interface methods.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This allows for direct calling in-process and via the COM/DCOM sub-system access between processes and computers.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A **coclass**, a COM class, implements one or more interfaces.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] It is identified by a class ID, called CLSID which is GUID, and by a human-readable programmatic identifier, called ProgID.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A coclass is created via one of these identifiers.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Each COM **interface** extends the `IUnknown` interface, which exposes methods for reference counting and for accessing the other interfaces of the object – similar to type conversion, a.k.a. type casting.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] An interface is identified by an interface ID (IID), a GUID.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A **custom interface**, anything derived from `IUnknown`, provides early bound access via a pointer to a virtual method table that contains a list of pointers to the functions that implement the functions declared in the interface, in the order they are declared.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] An in-process invocation overhead is, therefore, comparable to a C++ virtual method call.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Dispatching, a.k.a. late bound access, is provided by implementing `IDispatch`.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Dispatching allows access from a wider range of programming contexts than a custom interface.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Like many object-oriented languages, COM provides a separation of interface from implementation.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This distinction is especially strong in COM where an object has no default interface.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A client must request an interface to have any access.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM supports multiple implementations of the same interface, so that clients can choose which implementation of an interface to use.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A COM **type library** defines COM metadata, such as coclasses and interfaces.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A library can be defined as Interface definition language (IDL); a programming language independent syntax.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] IDL is similar to C++ with additional syntax for defining interfaces and coclasses.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] IDL also supports bracketed attributes before declarations to define metadata such as identifiers and relationships between parameters.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] An IDL file is compiled via the MIDL compiler.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] For use with C/C++, the MIDL compiler generates a header file with `struct` definitions to match the vtbls of the declared interfaces and a C file containing declarations of the interface GUIDs.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] C++ source code for a proxy module can also be generated by the MIDL compiler.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This proxy contains method stubs for converting COM calls into remote procedure calls to enable DCOM for out-of-process communication.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] MIDL can generate a binary type library (TLB) that can be used by other tools to support access from other context.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] The following IDL code declares a coclass named SomeClass which implements an interface named ISomeInterface.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This is conceptually equivalent to the following C++ code where ISomeInterface is a pure virtual class, a.k.a. abstract base class.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] In C++, COM objects are instantiated via the COM subsystem CoCreateInstance function that takes the CLSID and IID.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A COM object uses reference counting to manage object lifetime.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] An object's reference count is controlled by the clients through the `IUnknown` `AddRef` and `Release` methods.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM objects are responsible for freeing their own memory when the reference count drops to zero.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Visual Basic) provide automatic reference counting to simplify object use.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] In C++, a smart pointer can be used to automate reference count management.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] For remote objects, not all reference count calls are sent over the wire.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A proxy keeps only one reference on the remote object and maintains its own local reference count.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] To simplify COM development for C++ developers, Microsoft introduced ATL (Active Template Library).
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] ATL provides a relatively high-level COM development paradigm.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] It also shields COM client application developers from the need to directly maintain reference counting, by providing smart pointer types.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Other libraries and languages that are COM-aware include the Microsoft Foundation Classes, the VC Compiler COM Support, VBScript, Visual Basic, ECMAScript (JavaScript) and Borland Delphi.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM is a language agnostic binary standard that allows objects to be used in any programming context able to access its binary interfaces.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM client software is responsible for enabling the COM sub-system, instantiating and reference-counting COM objects and querying objects for supported interfaces.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] The Microsoft Visual C++ compiler supports extensions to the C++ language, referred to as *C++ Attributes*, that are designed to simplify COM development and minimize boilerplate code required to implement COM servers in C++.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Originally, type library metadata was required to be stored in the system registry.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A COM client would use the registry information for object creation.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Registration-free (RegFree) COM was introduced with Windows XP to allow storing type library metadata as an assembly manifest either as a resource in the executable file or in a separate file installed with the component.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This allows multiple versions of the same component to be installed on the same computer, in different directories.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This technology has limited support for EXE COM servers and cannot be used for system-wide components such as MDAC, MSXML, DirectX or Internet Explorer.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] During application loading, the Windows loader searches for the manifest.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] If it is present, the loader adds information from it to the activation context.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] When the COM class factory tries to instantiate a class, the activation context is first checked to see if an implementation for the CLSID can be found.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Only if the lookup fails, the registry is scanned.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A COM object can be created without type library information, and instead only a path to the DLL file and CLSID.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A client can use the COM DLL function `DllGetClassObject` with the CLSID and IID_IClassFactory to create an instance of a factory object.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] The client can then use the factory object's `CreateInstance` to create an instance.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This is the same process the COM sub-system uses.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] If an object created this way creates another object, it will do so in the usual way (using the registry or manifest).
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] But it can create internal objects (which may not be registered at all), and hand out references to interfaces to them, using its own private knowledge.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A COM object can be transparently created and used from within the same process (in-process), across process boundaries (out-of-process), or remotely over the network (DCOM).
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Out-of-process and remote objects use marshalling to serialize method calls and return values over process or network boundaries.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This marshalling is invisible to the client, which accesses the object as if it were a local in-process object.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] In COM, threading is addressed through a concept known as *apartments*.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] An individual COM object lives in exactly one apartment, which might either be single-threaded or multi-threaded.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] There are three types of apartments in COM: *Single-Threaded Apartment (STA)*, *Multi-Threaded Apartment (MTA)*, and *Thread Neutral Apartment* (NA).
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Each apartment represents one mechanism whereby an object's internal state may be synchronized across multiple threads.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] A process can consist of multiple COM objects, some of which may use STA and others of which may use MTA.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] All threads accessing COM objects similarly live in one apartment.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] The choice of apartment for COM objects and threads are determined at run-time, and cannot be changed.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Threads and objects which belong to the same apartment follow the same thread access rules.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Method calls which are made inside the same apartment are therefore performed directly without any assistance from COM.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Method calls made across apartments are achieved via marshalling.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This requires the use of proxies and stubs.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] COM is relatively complex especially compared to more modern component technologies such as .NET.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] When an STA is initialized it creates a hidden window that is used for inter-apartment and inter-process message routing.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This window must have its message queue regularly "pumped".
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This construct is known as a "message pump".
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] On earlier versions of Windows, failure to do so could cause system-wide deadlocks.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This problem is complicated by some Windows APIs that initialize COM as part of their implementation, which causes a "leak" of implementation details.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Reference counting within COM may cause problems if two or more objects are circularly referenced.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] The design of an application must take this into account so that objects are not left orphaned.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Objects may also be left with active reference counts if the COM "event sink" model is used.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Since the object that fires the event needs a reference to the object reacting to the event, the latter's reference count will never reach zero.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Reference cycles are typically broken using either out-of-band termination or split identities.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] In the out-of-band termination technique, an object exposes a method which, when called, forces it to drop its references to other objects, thereby breaking the cycle.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] In the split identity technique, a single implementation exposes two separate COM objects (also known as identities).
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] This creates a weak reference between the COM objects, preventing a reference cycle.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Because in-process COM components are implemented in DLL files and registration only allows for a single version per CLSID, they might in some situations be subject to the "DLL Hell" effect.
[src:opc-classic/component-object-model] Registration-free COM capability eliminates this problem for in-process components; registration-free COM is not available for out-of-process servers.
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] The extension COM into Distributed COM was due to extensive use of DCE/RPC (Distributed Computing Environment/Remote Procedure Calls) – more specifically Microsoft's enhanced version, known as MSRPC.
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] One of the key factors in solving these problems is the use of DCE/RPC as the underlying RPC mechanism behind DCOM.
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] DCE/RPC has strictly defined rules regarding marshalling and who is responsible for freeing memory.
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] Proponents of both of these technologies saw them as one day becoming the model for code and service-reuse over the Internet.
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] However, the difficulties involved in getting either of these technologies to work over Internet firewalls, and on unknown and insecure machines, meant that normal HTTP requests in combination with web browsers won out over both of them.
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] Microsoft, at one point, attempted to remediate these shortcomings by adding an extra HTTP transport to DCE/RPC called *ncacn_http* (Network Computing Architecture connection-oriented protocol).
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] DCOM was publicly launched as a beta for Windows 95 September 18, 1996.
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] As part of the initiative that began at Microsoft as part of Secure Development Lifecycle to re-architect insecure code, DCOM saw some significant security-focused changes in Windows XP Service Pack 2.
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] In response to a security vulnerability reported by Tencent Security Xuanwu Lab in June 2021, Microsoft released security updates for several versions of Windows and Windows Server, hardening access to DCOM.
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] In 1995, Digital and Microsoft announced Affinity for OpenVMS (also known as NT Affinity) which was intended to allow OpenVMS to serve as the persistence layer for Windows NT client-server applications.
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] As part of this initiative, an implementation of the Distributed Component Object Model (DCOM) was added to OpenVMS Alpha.
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] In order to support DCOM, VMS was provided with implementations of the Windows Registry, NTLM authentication, and a subset of Win32 APIs needed to support COM.
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] DCOM was first added to OpenVMS V7.2-1 for the Alpha.
[src:opc-classic/distributed-component-object-model] A similar implementation of DCOM was added to Digital Unix as part of the AllConnect program.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] After the initial release in 1996, the OPC Foundation was created to maintain the standards.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] Since OPC has been adopted beyond the field of process control, the OPC Foundation changed its name to Open Platform Communications in 2011.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] The name change reflects the applications of OPC technology for applications in building automation, discrete manufacturing, process control and others.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] OPC has also grown beyond its original OLE implementation to include other data transportation technologies including Microsoft Corporation's .NET Framework, XML, and even the OPC Foundation's binary-encoded TCP format.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] The OPC specification was based on the OLE, COM, and DCOM technologies developed by Microsoft Corporation for the Microsoft Windows operating system family.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] The specification defined a standard set of objects, interfaces e.g.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] IDL and methods for use in process control and manufacturing automation applications to facilitate interoperability.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] The most common OPC specification is OPC Data Access, which is used for reading and writing real-time data.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] When vendors refer to "OPC" generically, they typically mean OPC Data Access (OPC DA).
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] OPC DA itself has gone through three major revisions since its inception.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] Versions are backwards compatible, in that a version 3 OPC Server can still be accessed by a version 1 OPC Client, since the specifications add functionality, but still require the older version to be implemented as well.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] However, a client could be written that does not support the older functions since everything can be done using the newer ones, thus a DA-3-compatible client will not necessarily work with a DA 1.0 Server.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] In addition OPC DA specification, the OPC Foundation maintains the OPC Historical Data Access (HDA) specification.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] In contrast to the real time data that is accessible with OPC DA, OPC HDA allows access and retrieval of archived data.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] The OPC Alarms and Events specification is maintained by the OPC Foundation, and defines the exchange of alarm and event type message information, as well as variable states and state management.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] By 2002, the specification was compared to Fieldbus and other previous standards.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] An OPC Express Interface, known as OPC Xi, was approved in November, 2009, for the .NET Framework.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] OPC Xi used Windows Communication Foundation instead of DCOM, so it can be configured for communication across the enhanced security of network address translation (NAT).
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] About the same time, the OPC Unified Architecture (UA) was developed for platform independence.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] UA can be implemented with Java, Microsoft .NET, or C, eliminating the need to use a Microsoft Windows platform of earlier OPC versions.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] UA combined the functionality of the existing OPC interfaces with new technologies such as XML and Web services to deliver higher level manufacturing execution system (MES) and enterprise resource planning (ERP) support.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] The first working group for UA met in 2003, version 1.0 was published in 2006.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] On September 16, 2010, The OPC Foundation and the MTConnect Institute announced cooperation to ensure interoperability and consistency between the two standards.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] OPC was designed to provide a common bridge for Windows-based software applications and process control hardware.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] Standards define consistent methods of accessing field data from plant floor devices.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] This method remains the same regardless of the type and source of data.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] An OPC Server for one hardware device provides the same methods for an OPC client to access its data as any other OPC Server for any hardware device.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] The aim was to reduce the amount of duplicated effort required from hardware manufacturers and their software partners, and from the supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) and other human-machine interface (HMI) producers in order to interface the two.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] Once a hardware manufacturer had developed their OPC Server for the new hardware device, their work was done with regards to allowing any 'top end' to access their device, and once the SCADA producer had developed their OPC client, it allowed access to any hardware with an OPC compliant server.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] OPC servers provide a method for different software packages (as long as it is an OPC client) to access data from a process control device, such as a programmable logic controller (PLC) or distributed control system (DCS).
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] Traditionally, any time a package needed access to data from a device, a custom interface or driver had to be written.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] There is nothing in the OPC specifications to restrict the server to providing access to a process control device.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] OPC Servers can be written for anything from getting the internal temperature of a microprocessor to the current temperature in Monument Valley.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] Once an OPC Server is written for a particular device, it can be reused by any application that is able to act as an OPC client.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] OPC servers can be linked and communicate to other servers.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] OPC servers use Microsoft's OLE technology (also known as the Component Object Model, or COM) to communicate with clients.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] COM technology permits a standard for real-time information exchange between software applications and process hardware to be defined.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] Some OPC specifications are published, but others are available only to members of the OPC Foundation.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] So while no company "owns" OPC and anyone can develop an OPC server whether or not they are a member of the OPC Foundation, non-members will not necessarily be using the latest specifications.
[src:opc-classic/ole-for-process-control] It is up to each company that requires OPC products to ensure that their products are certified and that their system integrators have the necessary training.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] In IPC, control theory provides the theoretical framework to understand system dynamics, predict outcomes and design control strategies to ensure predetermined objectives, utilizing concepts like feedback loops, stability analysis and controller design.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] On the other hand, the physical apparatus of IPC, based on automation technologies, consists of several components.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Firstly, a network of sensors continuously measure various process variables (such as temperature, pressure, etc.) and product quality variables.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] This creates a continuous closed-loop cycle of measurement, comparison, control action, and re-evaluation which guarantees that the process remains within established parameters.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The HMI (Human-Machine Interface) acts as the "control panel" for the IPC system where small number of human operators can monitor the process and make informed decisions regarding adjustments.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] IPCs can range from controlling the temperature and level of a single process vessel (controlled environment tank for mixing, separating, reacting, or storing materials in industrial processes.) to a complete chemical processing plant with several thousand control feedback loops.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] IPC provides several critical benefits to manufacturing companies.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] By maintaining a tight control over key process variables, it helps reduce energy use, minimize waste and shorten downtime for peak efficiency and reduced costs.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] It ensures consistent and improved product quality with little variability, which satisfies the customers and strengthens the company's reputation.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] It improves safety by detecting and alerting human operators about potential issues early, thus preventing accidents, equipment failures, process disruptions and costly downtime.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Analyzing trends and behaviors in the vast amounts of data collected real-time helps engineers identify areas of improvement, refine control strategies and continuously enhance production efficiency using a data-driven approach.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] IPC is used across a wide range of industries where precise control is important.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The applications can range from controlling the temperature and level of a single process vessel, to a complete chemical processing plant with several thousand control loops.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] In automotive manufacturing, IPC ensures consistent quality by meticulously controlling processes like welding and painting.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Mining operations are optimized with IPC monitoring ore crushing and adjusting conveyor belt speeds for maximum output.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Dredging benefits from precise control of suction pressure, dredging depth and sediment discharge rate by IPC, ensuring efficient and sustainable practices.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Pulp and paper production leverages IPC to regulate chemical processes (e.g., pH and bleach concentration) and automate paper machine operations to control paper sheet moisture content and drying temperature for consistent quality.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] In chemical plants, it ensures the safe and efficient production of chemicals by controlling temperature, pressure and reaction rates.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Oil refineries use it to smoothly convert crude oil into gasoline and other petroleum products.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] In power plants, it helps maintain stable operating conditions necessary for a continuous electricity supply.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] In food and beverage production, it helps ensure consistent texture, safety and quality.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Pharmaceutical companies relies on it to produce life-saving drugs safely and effectively.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The development of large industrial process control systems has been instrumental in enabling the design of large high volume and complex processes, which could not be otherwise economically or safely operated.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Early process control breakthroughs came most frequently in the form of water control devices.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Ktesibios of Alexandria is credited for inventing float valves to regulate water level of water clocks in the 3rd century BC.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] In the 1st century AD, Heron of Alexandria invented a water valve similar to the fill valve used in modern toilets.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Later process controls inventions involved basic physics principles.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel invented a bimetallic thermostat for controlling the temperature in a furnace.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] In 1681, Denis Papin discovered the pressure inside a vessel could be regulated by placing weights on top of the vessel lid.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] In 1745, Edmund Lee created the fantail to improve windmill efficiency; a fantail was a smaller windmill placed 90° of the larger fans to keep the face of the windmill pointed directly into the oncoming wind.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] With the dawn of the Industrial Revolution in the 1760s, process controls inventions were aimed to replace human operators with mechanized processes.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] In 1784, Oliver Evans created a water-powered flourmill which operated using buckets and screw conveyors.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Henry Ford applied the same theory in 1910 when the assembly line was created to decrease human intervention in the automobile production process.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] For continuously variable process control it was not until 1922 that a formal control law for what we now call PID control or three-term control was first developed using theoretical analysis, by Russian American engineer Nicolas Minorsky.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Minorsky was researching and designing automatic ship steering for the US Navy and based his analysis on observations of a helmsman.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] He noted the helmsman steered the ship based not only on the current course error, but also on past error, as well as the current rate of change; this was then given a mathematical treatment by Minorsky.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] His goal was stability, not general control, which simplified the problem significantly.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] While proportional control provided stability against small disturbances, it was insufficient for dealing with a steady disturbance, notably a stiff gale (due to steady-state error), which required adding the integral term.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Finally, the derivative term was added to improve stability and control.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Initially, control would be from panels local to the process plant.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] However this required a large manpower resource to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently-staffed central control room.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Effectively this was the centralization of all the localized panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easier overview of the process.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Often the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were transmitted back to plant.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, and continual operator movement within the control room was required to view different parts of the process.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] With the coming of electronic processors and graphic displays it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] These could be distributed around the plant, and communicate with the graphic display in the control room or rooms.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The distributed control system (DCS) was born.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The introduction of DCSs allowed easy interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The accompanying diagram is a general model which shows functional manufacturing levels in a large process using processor and computer-based control.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] To determine the fundamental model for any process, the inputs and outputs of the system are defined differently than for other chemical processes.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The balance equations are defined by the control inputs and outputs rather than the material inputs.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The control model is a set of equations used to predict the behavior of a system and can help determine what the response to change will be.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The state variable (x) is a measurable variable that is a good indicator of the state of the system, such as temperature (energy balance), volume (mass balance) or concentration (component balance).
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Input variable (u) is a specified variable that commonly include flow rates.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The entering and exiting flows are both considered control inputs.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The control input can be classified as a manipulated, disturbance, or unmonitored variable.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Parameters (p) are usually a physical limitation and something that is fixed for the system, such as the vessel volume or the viscosity of the material.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Output (y) is the metric used to determine the behavior of the system.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The control output can be classified as measured, unmeasured, or unmonitored.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Processes can be characterized as batch, continuous, or hybrid.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Batch applications require that specific quantities of raw materials be combined in specific ways for particular duration to produce an intermediate or end result.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] One example is the production of adhesives and glues, which normally require the mixing of raw materials in a heated vessel for a period of time to form a quantity of end product.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Other important examples are the production of food, beverages and medicine.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Batch processes are generally used to produce a relatively low to intermediate quantity of product per year (a few pounds to millions of pounds).
[src:opc-classic/process-control] A continuous physical system is represented through variables that are smooth and uninterrupted in time.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The control of the water temperature in a heating jacket, for example, is an example of continuous process control.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Some important continuous processes are the production of fuels, chemicals and plastics.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Continuous processes in manufacturing are used to produce very large quantities of product per year (millions to billions of pounds).
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Such controls use feedback such as in the PID controller A PID Controller includes proportional, integrating, and derivative controller functions.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Applications having elements of batch and continuous process control are often called hybrid applications.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The fundamental building block of any industrial control system is the control loop, which controls just one process variable.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] An example is shown in the accompanying diagram, where the flow rate in a pipe is controlled by a PID controller, assisted by what is effectively a cascaded loop in the form of a valve servo-controller to ensure correct valve positioning.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Some large systems may have several hundreds or thousands of control loops.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] In complex processes the loops are interactive, so that the operation of one loop may affect the operation of another.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The system diagram for representing control loops is a Piping and instrumentation diagram.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Commonly used control systems include programmable logic controller (PLC), Distributed Control System (DCS) or SCADA.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] If a control valve were used to hold level in a tank, the level controller would compare the equivalent reading of a level sensor to the level setpoint and determine whether more or less valve opening was necessary to keep the level constant.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] A cascaded flow controller could then calculate the change in the valve position.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The economic nature of many products manufactured in batch and continuous processes require highly efficient operation due to thin margins.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The competing factor in process control is that products must meet certain specifications in order to be satisfactory.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] These specifications can come in two forms: a minimum and maximum for a property of the material or product, or a range within which the property must be.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] All loops are susceptible to disturbances and therefore a buffer must be used on process set points to ensure disturbances do not cause the material or product to go out of specifications.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] This buffer comes at an economic cost (i.e. additional processing, maintaining elevated or depressed process conditions, etc.).
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Process efficiency can be enhanced by reducing the margins necessary to ensure product specifications are met.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] This can be done by improving the control of the process to minimize the effect of disturbances on the process.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] The efficiency is improved in a two step method of narrowing the variance and shifting the target.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Margins can be narrowed through various process upgrades (i.e. equipment upgrades, enhanced control methods, etc.).
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Once margins are narrowed, an economic analysis can be done on the process to determine how the set point target is to be shifted.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Less conservative process set points lead to increased economic efficiency.
[src:opc-classic/process-control] Effective process control strategies increase the competitive advantage of manufacturers who employ them.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA computer system.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The subordinated operations, e.g. the real-time control logic or controller calculations, are performed by networked modules connected to the field sensors and actuators.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The SCADA concept was developed to be a universal means of remote-access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers and allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:opc-classic/scada] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become similar to DCSs in function, while using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:opc-classic/scada] They can control large-scale processes spanning multiple sites, and work over large distances.
[src:opc-classic/scada] It is one of the most commonly used types of industrial control systems.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The key attribute of a SCADA system is its ability to perform a supervisory operation over a variety of other proprietary devices.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Level 1 contains the programmable logic controllers (PLCs) or remote terminal units (RTUs).
[src:opc-classic/scada] Level 2 contains the SCADA to readings and equipment status reports that are communicated to level 2 SCADA as required.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Data is then compiled and formatted in such a way that a control room operator using the human-machine interface (HMI) can make supervisory decisions to adjust or override normal RTU (PLC) controls.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Data may also be fed to a historian, often built on a commodity database management system, to allow trending and other analytical auditing.
[src:opc-classic/scada] SCADA systems typically use a *tag database*, which contains data elements called *tags* or *points*, which relate to specific instrumentation or actuators within the process system.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Data is accumulated against these unique process control equipment tag references.
[src:opc-classic/scada] This is the core of the SCADA system, gathering data on the process and sending control commands to the field connected devices.
[src:opc-classic/scada] It refers to the computer and software responsible for communicating with the field connection controllers, which are RTUs and PLCs, and includes the HMI software running on operator workstations.
[src:opc-classic/scada] In smaller SCADA systems, the supervisory computer may be composed of a single PC, in which case the HMI is a part of this computer.
[src:opc-classic/scada] In larger SCADA systems, the master station may include several HMIs hosted on client computers, multiple servers for data acquisition, distributed software applications, and disaster recovery sites.
[src:opc-classic/scada] formation providing continuous control and monitoring in the event of a server malfunction or breakdown.
[src:opc-classic/scada] connect to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory computer system.
[src:opc-classic/scada] system, using radio, GSM or satellite for communications, and being ruggedised to survive from -20C to +70C or even -40C to +85C without external heating or cooling equipment.
[src:opc-classic/scada] PLCs are connected to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory system.
[src:opc-classic/scada] In factory automation, PLCs typically have a high speed connection to the SCADA system.
[src:opc-classic/scada] In remote applications, such as a large water treatment plant, PLCs may connect directly to SCADA over a wireless link, or more commonly, utilise an RTU for the communications management.
[src:opc-classic/scada] For economical reasons, PLCs are often used for remote sites where there is a large I/O count, rather than utilising an RTU alone.
[src:opc-classic/scada] This connects the supervisory computer system to the RTUs and PLCs, and may use industry standard or manufacturer proprietary protocols.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Both RTUs and PLCs operate autonomously on the near-real time control of the process, using the last command given from the supervisory system.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Failure of the communications network does not necessarily stop the plant process controls, and on resumption of communications, the operator can continue with monitoring and control.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Some critical systems will have dual redundant data highways, often cabled via diverse routes.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The HMI is the operator window of the supervisory system.
[src:opc-classic/scada] It presents plant information to the operating personnel graphically in the form of mimic diagrams, which are a schematic representation of the plant being controlled, and alarm and event logging pages.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The HMI is linked to the SCADA supervisory computer to provide live data to drive the mimic diagrams, alarm displays and trending graphs.
[src:opc-classic/scada] In many installations the HMI is the graphical user interface for the operator, collects all data from external devices, creates reports, performs alarming, sends notifications, etc.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Mimic diagrams consist of line graphics and schematic symbols to represent process elements, or may consist of digital photographs of the process equipment overlain with animated symbols.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Supervisory operation of the plant is by means of the HMI, with operators issuing commands using mouse pointers, keyboards and touch screens.
[src:opc-classic/scada] For example, a symbol of a pump can show the operator that the pump is running, and a flow meter symbol can show how much fluid it is pumping through the pipe.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The operator can switch the pump off from the mimic by a mouse click or screen touch.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The HMI will show the flow rate of the fluid in the pipe decrease in real time.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The HMI package for a SCADA system typically includes a drawing program that the operators or system maintenance personnel use to change the way these points are represented in the interface.
[src:opc-classic/scada] These representations can be as simple as an on-screen traffic light, which represents the state of an actual traffic light in the field, or as complex as a multi-projector display representing the position of all of the elevators in a skyscraper or all of the trains on a railway.
[src:opc-classic/scada] is a software service within the HMI which accumulates time-stamped data, events, and alarms in a database which can be queried or used to populate graphic trends in the HMI.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The historian is a client that requests data from a data acquisition server.
[src:opc-classic/scada] An important part of most SCADA implementations is alarm handling.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The system monitors whether certain alarm conditions are satisfied, to determine when an alarm event has occurred.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Once an alarm event has been detected, one or more actions are taken (such as the activation of one or more alarm indicators, and perhaps the generation of email or text messages so that management or remote SCADA operators are informed).
[src:opc-classic/scada] In many cases, a SCADA operator may have to acknowledge the alarm event; this may deactivate some alarm indicators, whereas other indicators remain active until the alarm conditions are cleared.
[src:opc-classic/scada] "Smart" RTUs, or standard PLCs, are capable of autonomously executing simple logic processes without involving the supervisory computer.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Unlike a procedural language like C or FORTRAN, IEC 61131-3 has minimal training requirements by virtue of resembling historic physical control arrays.
[src:opc-classic/scada] This allows SCADA system engineers to perform both the design and implementation of a program to be executed on an RTU or PLC.
[src:opc-classic/scada] A programmable automation controller (PAC) is a compact controller that combines the features and capabilities of a PC-based control system with that of a typical PLC.
[src:opc-classic/scada] PACs are deployed in SCADA systems to provide RTU and PLC functions.
[src:opc-classic/scada] In many electrical substation SCADA applications, "distributed RTUs" use information processors or station computers to communicate with digital protective relays, PACs, and other devices for I/O, and communicate with the SCADA master in lieu of a traditional RTU.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Since about 1998, virtually all major PLC manufacturers have offered integrated HMI/SCADA systems, many of them using open and non-proprietary communications protocols.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The Remote Terminal Unit (RTU) connects to physical equipment.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Typically, an RTU converts the electrical signals from the equipment to digital values.
[src:opc-classic/scada] By converting and sending these electrical signals out to equipment the RTU can control equipment.
[src:opc-classic/scada] SCADA systems have traditionally used combinations of radio and direct wired connections, although SONET/SDH is also frequently used for large systems such as railways and power stations.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The remote management or monitoring function of a SCADA system is often referred to as telemetry.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Some users want SCADA data to travel over their pre-established corporate networks or to share the network with other applications.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The legacy of the early low-bandwidth protocols remains, though.
[src:opc-classic/scada] SCADA protocols are designed to be very compact.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Many are designed to send information only when the master station polls the RTU.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Typical legacy SCADA protocols include Modbus RTU, RP-570, Profibus and Conitel.
[src:opc-classic/scada] These communication protocols, with the exception of Modbus (Modbus has been made open by Schneider Electric), are all SCADA-vendor specific but are widely adopted and used.
[src:opc-classic/scada] These communication protocols are standardized and recognized by all major SCADA vendors.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Many of these protocols now contain extensions to operate over TCP/IP.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Although the use of conventional networking specifications, such as TCP/IP, blurs the line between traditional and industrial networking, they each fulfill fundamentally differing requirements.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Network simulation can be used in conjunction with SCADA simulators to perform various 'what-if' analyses.
[src:opc-classic/scada] With increasing security demands (such as North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) and critical infrastructure protection (CIP) in the US), there is increasing use of satellite-based communication.
[src:opc-classic/scada] This has the key advantages that the infrastructure can be self-contained (not using circuits from the public telephone system), can have built-in encryption, and can be engineered to the availability and reliability required by the SCADA system operator.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Earlier experiences using consumer-grade VSAT were poor.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Modern carrier-class systems provide the quality of service required for SCADA.
[src:opc-classic/scada] RTUs and other automatic controller devices were developed before the advent of industry wide standards for interoperability.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The result is that developers and their management created a multitude of control protocols.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Among the larger vendors, there was also the incentive to create their own protocol to "lock in" their customer base.
[src:opc-classic/scada] A list of automation protocols is compiled here.
[src:opc-classic/scada] An example of efforts by vendor groups to standardize automation protocols is the OPC-UA (formerly "OLE for process control" now Open Platform Communications Unified Architecture).
[src:opc-classic/scada] Early SCADA system computing was done by large minicomputers.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Common network services did not exist at the time SCADA was developed.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Thus SCADA systems were independent systems with no connectivity to other systems.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The communication protocols used were strictly proprietary at that time.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The first-generation SCADA system redundancy was achieved using a back-up mainframe system connected to all the remote terminal unit sites and was used in the event of failure of the primary mainframe system.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Some first generation SCADA systems were developed as "turn key" operations that ran on minicomputers such as the PDP-11 series.
[src:opc-classic/scada] SCADA information and command processing were distributed across multiple stations which were connected through a LAN.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Information was shared in near real time.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Each station was responsible for a particular task, which reduced the cost as compared to first generation SCADA.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The network protocols used were still not standardized.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Since these protocols were proprietary, very few people beyond the developers knew enough to determine how secure a SCADA installation was.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Security of the SCADA installation was usually overlooked.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Similar to a distributed architecture, any complex SCADA can be reduced to the simplest components and connected through communication protocols.
[src:opc-classic/scada] In the case of a networked design, the system may be spread across more than one LAN network called a process control network (PCN) and separated geographically.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Several distributed architecture SCADAs running in parallel, with a single supervisor and historian, could be considered a network architecture.
[src:opc-classic/scada] This allows for a more cost-effective solution in very large scale systems.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The growth of the internet has led SCADA systems to implement web technologies allowing users to view data, exchange information and control processes from anywhere in the world through standard web protocols such as HTTPS and WebSocket for live updates.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The early 2000s saw the proliferation of Web SCADA systems.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Web SCADA systems use web browsers such as Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox as the graphical user interface (GUI) for the operators HMI.
[src:opc-classic/scada] This simplifies the client side installation and enables users to access the system from various platforms with web browsers such as servers, personal computers, laptops, tablets and mobile phones.
[src:opc-classic/scada] SCADA systems that tie together decentralized facilities such as power, oil, gas pipelines, water distribution and wastewater collection systems were designed to be open, robust, and easily operated and repaired, but not necessarily secure.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The move from proprietary technologies to more standardized and open solutions together with the increased number of connections between SCADA systems, office networks and the Internet has made them more vulnerable to types of network attacks that are relatively common in computer security.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Security researcher Jerry Brown submitted a similar advisory regarding a buffer overflow vulnerability in a Wonderware InBatchClient ActiveX control.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Both vendors made updates available prior to public vulnerability release.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Mitigation recommendations were standard patching practices and requiring VPN access for secure connectivity.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Consequently, the security of some SCADA-based systems has come into question as they are seen as potentially vulnerable to cyber attacks.
[src:opc-classic/scada] SCADA systems are used to control and monitor physical processes, examples of which are transmission of electricity, transportation of gas and oil in pipelines, water distribution, traffic lights, and other systems used as the basis of modern society.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The security of these SCADA systems is important because compromise or destruction of these systems would impact multiple areas of society far removed from the original compromise.
[src:opc-classic/scada] For example, a blackout caused by a compromised electrical SCADA system would cause financial losses to all the customers that received electricity from that source.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Legacy SCADA deployments can remain difficult to secure because control equipment is often geographically distributed, long-lived, and costly to replace or patch.
[src:opc-classic/scada] There are many threat vectors to a modern SCADA system.
[src:opc-classic/scada] One is the threat of unauthorized access to the control software, whether it is human access or changes induced intentionally or accidentally by virus infections and other software threats residing on the control host machine.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Another is the threat of packet access to the network segments hosting SCADA devices.
[src:opc-classic/scada] In many cases, the control protocol lacks any form of cryptographic security, allowing an attacker to control a SCADA device by sending commands over a network.
[src:opc-classic/scada] In many cases SCADA users have assumed that having a VPN offered sufficient protection, unaware that security can be trivially bypassed with physical access to SCADA-related network jacks and switches.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Industrial control vendors suggest approaching SCADA security like Information Security with a defense in depth strategy that leverages common IT practices.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Apart from that, research has shown that the architecture of SCADA systems has several other vulnerabilities, including direct tampering with RTUs, communication links from RTUs to the control center, and IT software and databases in the control center.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The RTUs could, for instance, be targets of deception attacks injecting false data or denial-of-service attacks.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The reliable function of SCADA systems in our modern infrastructure may be crucial to public health and safety.
[src:opc-classic/scada] As such, attacks on these systems may directly or indirectly threaten public health and safety.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Such an attack has already occurred, carried out on Maroochy Shire Council's sewage control system in Queensland, Australia.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Shortly after a contractor installed a SCADA system in January 2000, system components began to function erratically.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Pumps did not run when needed and alarms were not reported.
[src:opc-classic/scada] More critically, sewage flooded a nearby park and contaminated an open surface-water drainage ditch and flowed 500 meters to a tidal canal.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The SCADA system was directing sewage valves to open when the design protocol should have kept them closed.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Initially this was believed to be a system bug.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Monitoring of the system logs revealed the malfunctions were the result of cyber attacks.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Investigators reported 46 separate instances of malicious outside interference before the culprit was identified.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The attacks were made by a disgruntled ex-employee of the company that had installed the SCADA system.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The ex-employee was hoping to be hired by the utility full-time to maintain the system.
[src:opc-classic/scada] In April 2008, the *Commission to Assess the Threat to the United States from Electromagnetic Pulse (EMP) Attack* issued a *Critical Infrastructures Report* document which discussed the extreme vulnerability of SCADA systems to an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) event.
[src:opc-classic/scada] After testing and analysis, the commission concluded: "SCADA systems are vulnerable to EMP insult.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The large numbers and widespread reliance on such systems by all of the Nation’s critical infrastructures represent a systemic threat to their continued operation following an EMP event.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Many vendors of SCADA and control products have begun to address the risks posed by unauthorized access by developing lines of specialized industrial firewall and VPN solutions for TCP/IP-based SCADA networks as well as external SCADA monitoring and recording equipment.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The International Society of Automation (ISA) started formalizing SCADA security requirements in 2007 with a working group, WG4.
[src:opc-classic/scada] WG4 "deals specifically with unique technical requirements, measurements, and other features required to evaluate and assure security resilience and performance of industrial automation and control systems devices".
[src:opc-classic/scada] The increased interest in SCADA vulnerabilities has resulted in vulnerability researchers discovering vulnerabilities in commercial SCADA software and more general offensive SCADA techniques presented to the general security community.
[src:opc-classic/scada] In June 2010, anti-virus security company VirusBlokAda reported the first detection of malware that attacks SCADA systems (Siemens' WinCC/PCS 7 systems) running on Windows operating systems.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The malware is called Stuxnet and uses four zero-day attacks to install a rootkit which in turn logs into the SCADA's database and steals design and control files.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The malware is also capable of changing the control system and hiding those changes.
[src:opc-classic/scada] The malware was found on 14 systems, the majority of which were located in Iran.
[src:opc-classic/scada] In October 2013 *National Geographic* released a docudrama titled *American Blackout* which dealt with an imagined large-scale cyber attack on SCADA and the United States' electrical grid.
[src:opc-classic/scada] Both large and small systems can be built using the SCADA concept.
[src:opc-classic/scada] These systems can range from just tens to thousands of control loops, depending on the application.
[src:opc-classic/scada] However, SCADA systems may have security vulnerabilities, so the systems should be evaluated to identify risks and solutions implemented to mitigate those risks.
